    <title type="html"><![CDATA[Add Google Website Translator to your Octopress Blog]]></title>
    <link href="http://jatinganhotra.com/blog/2012/12/26/add-google-website-translator-to-your-octopress-blog/"/>
    <updated>2012-12-26T20:06:00+05:30</updated>
    <id>http://jatinganhotra.com/blog/2012/12/26/add-google-website-translator-to-your-octopress-blog</id>
    <content type="html"><![CDATA[<p><link href='http://fonts.googleapis.com/css?family=Coming+Soon&subset=latin,latin-ext' rel='stylesheet' type='text/css'></p>

<div>
<span style="float:right;" id="google_translate_element"></span>
<span style="float:right; font-family: 'Coming Soon', cursive;">Having trouble viewing in English, Choose Your Language : &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</span>
</div>


<BR>&nbsp;<BR>


<p>Most countries in the world have English as their <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_countries_where_English_is_an_official_language">official language</a>, but there are many countries where people <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:English-as-Official-Language_Map.png">don&#8217;t know English</a>. So, it&#8217;s good to have a website translator if people from such countries visit your blog. This article will show you how to add <a href="http://translate.google.com/manager/website/">Google Website Translator</a> to your <a href="http://octopress.org/">Octopress</a> blog.</p>

<p>Recently, <a href="http://www.google.com/">Google</a> <a href="http://googletranslate.blogspot.in/2012/05/now-you-can-polish-up-googles.html">announced in a post</a> on their <a href="http://googletranslate.blogspot.in/">Google translate blog</a> that they are introducing a beta website translator for blogs and websites.  Google translate currently works over 60 languages.  Once you add the customization meta tag to a webpage, visitors will see your customized translations whenever they translate the page, even when they use the feature in <a href="https://www.google.com/intl/en-GB/chrome/browser/features.html">Chrome</a> and <a href="http://www.google.com/toolbar/ie/index.html">Google Toolbar</a>. They’ll also now be able to &#8217;<a href="http://googleblog.blogspot.in/2007/03/suggest-better-translation.html">suggest a better translation</a>&#8217; when they notice a translation that’s not quite right, and later you can accept and use that suggestion on your site.</p>

<p>For more information about better translation and suggestion, refer <a href="http://translate.google.com/manager/website/">here</a>. You can follow these easy steps to add Google Website Translator to your Octopress blog:</p>

<h4>Step 1 : Get <code>&lt;meta&gt;</code> tag and <code>&lt;script&gt;</code>&#8217;s which the Website Translator plugin uses</h4>

<ol>
<li>Go to <a href="http://translate.google.com/manager/website/">Google Website Translator</a> and sign in with your Google account.</li>
<li>Enter the URL for your website and the original language of your website.</li>
<li>You can customize the plugin settings like <em>Translation languages (all/specific)</em>, <em>Display modes (Inline/Tabbed/Automatic)</em> etc. and whether you want to track Translation Traffic using Google Analytics.</li>
<li>Google translate will give you a <code>&lt;meta&gt;</code> tag and a <code>code snippet</code> with <code>&lt;div&gt;</code> and <code>&lt;script&gt;</code> tags.</li>
</ol>


<h4>Step 2 : Use the above snippet in your Octopress blog</h4>

<ol>
<li>Create a file <code>google_translate.html</code> in <code>source/_includes/</code>.</li>
<li>Add the <code>&lt;meta&gt;</code> tag and the <code>&lt;script&gt;</code> tags to this file.</li>
</ol>


<figure class='code'><div class="highlight"><table><tr><td class="gutter"><pre class="line-numbers"><span class='line-number'>1</span>
<span class='line-number'>2</span>
<span class='line-number'>3</span>
<span class='line-number'>4</span>
<span class='line-number'>5</span>
<span class='line-number'>6</span>
<span class='line-number'>7</span>
<span class='line-number'>8</span>
<span class='line-number'>9</span>
<span class='line-number'>10</span>
<span class='line-number'>11</span>
<span class='line-number'>12</span>
<span class='line-number'>13</span>
</pre></td><td class='code'><pre><code class=''><span class='line'>&lt;meta name="google-translate-customization" content="ABCDEFGHIJKLMNOPQRSTUVWXYZ"&gt;&lt;/meta&gt;
</span><span class='line'>&lt;script type="text/javascript"&gt;
</span><span class='line'>    function googleTranslateElementInit() {
</span><span class='line'>        new google.translate.TranslateElement({
</span><span class='line'>              pageLanguage: 'en', 
</span><span class='line'>              layout: google.translate.TranslateElement.InlineLayout.SIMPLE,
</span><span class='line'>              gaTrack: true,
</span><span class='line'>              gaId: 'UA-ABCDEFGH'},
</span><span class='line'>         'google_translate_element');
</span><span class='line'>}
</span><span class='line'>&lt;/script&gt;
</span><span class='line'>
</span><span class='line'>&lt;script type="text/javascript" src="http://jatinganhotra.com//translate.google.com/translate_a/element.js?cb=googleTranslateElementInit"&gt;&lt;/script&gt;</span></code></pre></td></tr></table></div></figure>


<p>If you observe carefully, you can look at the values of the parameters that you set when you got the code. e.g. I&#8217;m using <em>inline</em> styling with <em>Simple</em> layout and Google Analytics to track translation traffic.<br/>
3. Add the following line where you want to display the plugin.</p>

<figure class='code'><div class="highlight"><table><tr><td class="gutter"><pre class="line-numbers"><span class='line-number'>1</span>
</pre></td><td class='code'><pre><code class=''><span class='line'>&lt;div id="google_translate_element"&gt;</span></code></pre></td></tr></table></div></figure>


<p>
4. Include <code>google_translate.html</code> in the <code>&lt;head&gt;</code> tag in the file <code>source/_includes/head.html</code>, like <a href="https://github.com/imathis/octopress/blob/master/.themes/classic/source/_includes/head.html#L28">this</a>.<br/>
5. Run <code>rake generate ; rake preview</code> to play with it locally on your machine.</p>

<p>For more help, visit official <a href="https://support.google.com/translate/">Google translate support page</a> or if you face any problems, mention so in the comments section.</p>
]]></content>
